<A NAME="family"><HR>
From: John Eric Conner <joconner@linknet.kitsap.lib.wa.us><BR>
Date: Fri, 26 Apr 1996 17:29:53 -0700 (PDT)<BR>
Subject: C-NEWS: hotline.html (<A HREF="http://www.frc.org/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.html">http://www.frc.org/townhall/FRC/hotline/hotline.html</A>)<P>

   The Family Research Council has implemented a Legislative Hotline. By
   dialing 1-202-783-HOME, you will access current information on pending
   family issues in Washington, D.C., via telephone. The hotline is
   updated every Friday at 4:00 p.m.<P>
   
This Week's Message<P>

   
   
   Welcome to the FRC information line. This message will be updated on
   Friday, May 3 at the close of business.<P>
   
   Appropriations for the FY 96 finally pass. A bill is introduced to
   promote adoption. A hearing is called on the implications of Roe v.
   Wade on the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban.<P>
   
   
   
  Issue One.<P>
  
   
   
   Omnibus Appropriations bill. On Thursday April 25, Congress passed and
   the President signed HR 3019, a bill to fund a variety of federal
   agencies whose appropriations had previously been vetoed by President
   Bill Clinton or stalled in Congress. There were several provisions in
   the bill that the Family Research Council supported. A permanent
   protection for medical schools that decline to provide abortion
   training. The House accepted the Senate's Coats amendment which will
   protect these teaching institutions from a loss of federal funds that
   would have occurred as a result of a directive issued by the
   Accreditation Council for Graduate Medical Education (ACGME). The
   omnibus funding bill also contributes to the attainment of $23 billion
   in savings from FY 1995 levels. These savings have reduced federal
   borrowing obligations and contributed to the lowering of interest
   rates, thus increasing the purchasing power of millions of American
   families. This legislation also sustained the reductions in funding
   for the Legal Services Corporation (LSC) and the limitations on LSC
   activities that were contained in the Commerce-Justice-State
   Appropriations Conference Report (H.R. 2076), a bill that had earlier
   been vetoed by President Clinton. Given the LSC's track record,
   however, we remain highly skeptical that these limitations will be
   properly enforced. FRC will continue to call on Congress to eliminate
   funding for this seriously flawed program. Despite these very laudable
   components, we are very disappointed with some of the provisions in
   H.R. 3019. The restoration of funding for the intrusive Goals 2000
   program constitutes an inappropriate use of federal funds, although
   the funding level is slightly lower than in FY 1995. We disagree with
   the conferees' decision to drop a House provision relating to adoption
   petitions submitted by unmarried individuals in the District of
   Columbia. We also find it ironic that the conferees overturned the law
   calling for the discharge of HIV-positive military personnel even
   though Congress has not yet passed legislation to ensure treatment of
   newborn babies who are HIV infected.<P>
   
   
   
  Issue Two.<P>
  
   
   
   Adoption Promotion and Stability Act of 1996, HR 3286. Susan Molinari
   (R-NY) introduced HR 3286 on Wednesday, April 24. The Adoption
   Promotion and Stability Act of 1996 will include three main provisions
   to relieve the backlog of unadopted children in America today. A
   $5,000 Adoption Tax Credit, prohibitions on racial considerations
   being used to delay or deny adoptions and Reform of the Indian Child
   Welfare Act so that the rights of children, adoptive parents and birth
   parents are given proper consideration. The $5,000 Adoption Tax Credit
   provision had already been passed in a larger bill, the welfare reform
   bill (HR 4), that President Clinton vetoed, so there is hope that in
   this stand alone bill the credit will be successful. Congressman Jerry
   Solomon (R-NY) said the package "provided long overdue reform and a
   welcome emphasis on the strength and value of the family in today's
   society." At present there are over 500,000 children currently in the
   foster care system, and as it exists now, only about 50,000 children
   are cleared for adoption each year. The goal of this legislation is to
   break down the bureaucratic barriers and encourage families to adopt
   to help get these children out of the foster care system and into
   homes with loving families.<P>
   
   
   
  Issue Three.<P>
  
   
   
   Roe v. Wade Hearing. On Monday, April 22 House Judiciary Subcommittee
   Chairman Charles Canady (R-FL) called for hearings to examine the
   argument put forward by President Clinton in his veto message that the
   Constitution, as interpreted by Roe, protects the partial-birth
   abortion procedure. Canady said Roe only deals with fetuses, not with
   "partially born children." President Clinton vetoed the Partial-Birth
   Abortion Ban on April 10, 1996 making the argument that Roe v. Wade
   requires Congress to allow this procedure. However, congressman Canady
   and others argue that Roe v. Wade does not legalize this horrific
   procedure. In Texas a statute that was left intact by the Supreme
   Court outlawed killing a child "in the state of being born." This
   statute still exists. An incredibly moving witness in this hearing was
   Gianna Jessen, a 19 year-old survivor of an abortion. Miss Jessen
   stated, "My biological mother was 17 years old and 7-1/2 months
   pregnant when she made the decision to have a saline abortion. I am
   the person that she aborted. I lived instead of died, at 6:00 a.m. on
   the morning of April 6, 1977 ... Some have said that I am a 'botched
   abortion' -- a result of a job not well done.... I was just as much a
   person when I was aborted as I am today." Unfortunately this hearing
   was not well attended. Pro-abortion Rep. Pat Schroeder (D-CO)
   boycotted the hearing, saying it was only designed to "undermine the
   public's consistent and overwhelming support for Roe v. Wade." Ms.
   Schroeder and others continue to ignore the fact that 80 percent of
   Americans think abortion should either be legal only in the first
   trimester or should be prohibited except in very narrow cases like
   rape and incest or life of the mother (Nov. 94 Wirthlin Poll). Rep.
   Charles Canady states, "Americans never consented to, or indicated
   support for, abortion on demand -- but Roe v. Wade instituted it.<P>
   
   Thank you for calling the FRC Legislative Hotline.<BR>
- ----------------Fowarded by John Eric Conner <P>

