<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>ABIC - Term Limits for Congress/NFRW Magazine</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">

<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Bac
k in Charge" ISMAP></a><p>
<blockquote>
<center>
<img src="/abic/images/termlimt.gif" border="0" ALT="Term Limits">

</center>
by <A HREF="/abic/cdmbio.html.cgi">Cleta Deatherage Mitchell</A>
<p>
<H5>(originally printed in <a href="http://www.nfrw.org"><EM>The Republican Woman</EM></a>, June 1996)</H5></CENTER>
</P>

There are few issues that so clearly separate the Republicans and Democrats in Washington as the issue of amending the U.S. Constitution to provide for limits on the number of terms members of Congress may serve.  These facts tell the story:
<p><img src="/abic/images/mitchell.gif" ALIGN="right" ALT="Cleta Mitchell" HSPACE=25>
<UL>
<LI>There have been proposals in many Congresses, for decades, to amend the Constitution and enact congressional term limits:  under the Democrats, NO term limits measure was ever allowed to be debated or voted on in subcommittee, full committee or on the floor of either the House or Senate.
<P>
<LI>Conversely, in the first 100 days of the 104th Congress, the House of Representatives voted on the term limits constitutional amendment in the Judiciary Committee AND the floor of the House of Representatives.  
</ul><p>
<table hspace="10"><tr>
<td align="left"><hr><b>
THE DEMOCRATS IN CONGRESS<br> 
ARE VOTING AGAINST THE
 WILL<br> OF NOT ONLY
THE 
VAST MAJORITY OF PEOPLE 
IN THE COUNTRY, BUT 
AGAINST THE WISHES
OF 
THEIR OWN PARTY'S 
VOTERS AS WELL.</b><hr></td>
<td><ul>
<LI>In the historic first floor vote in the House in 1995, 82% of the House Republicans voted YES on term limits.  82% of the House Democrats voted NO. (See <a href="/abic/hstlvote.html.cgi">Chart</a>.)
<LI>Speaker Gingrich has already announced that term limits will be the first issue voted on in 1997 if the Republicans still control the House of Representatives.
</ul></td></tr></table>
<ul>
<LI>In the House Judiciary Committee in 1995, the Democrats unanimously voted AGAINST allowing term limits to be brought to the House floor for consideration.  Thanks to the Republican majority, the bill went to the floor despite the Democrats' opposition.
<P>
<LI>In the Senate this year, the Republicans unanimously voted in favor of bringing term limits to the floor for final consideration.  All but five Democrats voted AGAINST allowing the measure to proceed to the Senate floor for a final vote, thus blocking consideration and passage
 <P>
<LI>The GOP Platform has included term limits for members of Congress since 1984.
</UL><P>
What difference does it make if the Republicans overwhelmingly favor term limits and the Democrats in Washington oppose the issue so strongly?
<P>
The American people want to limit the terms of members of Congress!  In poll after poll, it is clear that the voters believe that congressional tenure should be limited and that congressional paychecks are like welfare checks:  it's okay to receive them for awhile but NOT for life.
<P>
In January, 1996, the Tarrance Group conducted a national poll of registered voters on behalf of the Term Limits Amendment National Campaign.  According to the data, 77% of the American people favor term limits while only 17% oppose the idea. (See <a href="/abic
/peoplepie.html.cgi">Chart</a>.) Of those, 59% strongly favor term limits and only 9% strongly oppose it.
<P>
The curious fact is that support for term limits never drops below 64% in any demographic or political group.  Democratic voters support term limits by a wide margin and conservative Democrats support term limits more strongly than any other group!
<P>
That means the Democrats in Congress are voting against the will of not only the vast majority of people in the country, but against the wishes of their own party's voters as well.
<P>
Term limits for Congress is a basic idea fundamental to our democracy:  Congress is supposed to be comprised of citizen representatives, not professional politicians.  The Democratic majority over the past four decades came to believe that Congress belonged to them, not the people of America -- and it is still difficult for Democrats to believe in the importance of returning Washington to the control of the American people.
<P>
There is another, more deeply philosophical basis for the congressional Democrats' opposition to term limits:  the national Democratic party basically believes in an unlimited federal government, with control over every aspect of our lives.  That notion has its origins in the idea of "no limits" for the Congress of the United States.  No limits on time, no limits on money, no limits on the federal government.
<P>
Most Americans believe that it is time to place limits on the money the Washington politicians can spend (the Balanced Budget Amendment) and limits on the time that politicians can spend in Washington -- the Term Limits Amendment.  These are the bookends of the GOP's Contract with America and they were fundamental principles of the design of the American system of government.  Because the founding fathers didn't write the principles down, our country has strayed badly from them -- and it is time to include in the Constitution the actual language of the principles that the framers clearly intended.
<P>
These are also principles in which most Republican members of Congress believe as well.  There are still some veteran Republican lawmakers who take the idea of term limits personally and can't get over the idea of how it will affect their careers.  They have difficulty getting past their personal involvement to see how the issue is fundamental to bringing the  federal government Leviathan under control for the sake of our children and grandchildren.
<p>
<table hspace="10"><tr><td width="60%">
George Will has written that term limits is more important to balancing the budget than the balanced budget amendment -- because the end of careerism in Congress will remove the incentives of members of Congress (from both parties) to use our tax dollars for their own reelection purposes by making voters dependent on Washington and the federal government instead of free enterprise and individual initiative.
</td><td><hr><b>
TERM LIMITS ARE IMPOSED ON THE PRESIDENT, 40 GOVERNORS,
21 STATE LEGISLATURES AND THOUSANDS OF LOCAL OFFICIALS
ACROSS THE NATION. WHY NOT CONGRESS?  
</b><hr></td></tr></table>
<p>
Term limits are imposed on the President, 40 Governors, 21 state legislatures and thousands of local officials across the nation.  Why not Congress?
<P>
In 1996, term limits is a key issue that Republican candidates and activists can use to demonstrate conclusively the differences between the parties.  It is an opportunity that should not be lost.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/abic/ftb/">Footing the Bill</a> - <a href="/abic/ptf/">Pointing the Finger</a> - <a href="/abic/sbg/welcome.html.cgi">Spotlight on Big Government</a><br>
