<html>
<head>
<title>ABICF - "Setting Limits" - "Hatfield and the Decoys"</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<a href="/abic/top.map"><img src="/abic/images/top.gif" border="0" ALT="Americans Back in Charge Foundation" ISMAP></a>
<p>
<center>
<h2>Hatfield and the Decoys</h2>
</center>
<p>
<p>



     When the Balanced Budget Amendment failed by one vote in the U.S. Senate in 1995, all eyes focused on Sen. Mark Hatfield, the lone Republican to vote against the BBA.  Less attention was paid to the real reason the BBA failed in 1995:  the six Democratic Senators who had previously voted "yes", had campaigned in favor of the BBA and then voted "no" when it really counted.  These are the "Decoys" who cost the American people passage of the BBA in 1995.
<p>
     In 1994, all of the following six senators had voted <i>for</i> a virtually identical Balanced Budget Amendment:
<p align=center>
Dianne Feinstein, D-California<br>
Wendell Ford, D-Kentucky<br>
Jeff Bingaman, D-New Mexico<br>
Byron Dorgan, D-North Dakota<br>
Ernest Hollings, D-South Carolina<br>
Tom Daschle, D-South Dakota<br>
</p align=center>
<p>
     What's worse, each and every one of them actually campaigned in favor of this issue.  They promised the voters of their states that they would vote "yes" when the amendment came to the floor.  They are the "Decoys" because they are Senators who pretended to support the BBA in an election year and switched in 1995 by voting "no".

<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Feinstein</b></h2>
     In a tough reelection race in 1994, Sen. Feinstein ran commercials touting her "yes" vote earlier that year on the BBA.  In October of 1994 during that campaign, while making an appearance on Larry King Live, Sen. Feinstein told a constituent caller that he could trust her to keep her promises.  When the caller asked her how she could expect him to vote for someone "wearing temporarily fiscally conservative clothing," she responded, "I said (in 1992) that I would vote for a balanced budget amendment and I voted for a balanced budget amendment."(1)  But when the vote actually came to the Senate floor in 1995 and was one vote away from passage, she voted "no".
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Ford and Hollings</b></h2>
	Sens. Ford and Hollings voted <i>for</i> the BBA in 1986 and 1994.  Sen. Ford was quoted as saying that Congress "must begin to regain control of our spending policies.  . . . An amendment to the Constitution would do just that."(2)
<p>
	Sen. Hollings has been a frequent cosponsor of the Balanced Budget Amendment.  In a column sent to newspapers in 1994, he wrote, "(o)nly an amendment to the Constitution will have the clout to force the executive and legislative branches to pay the bills."(3)  He has further said, "by writing a balanced budget into the basic law of the land, we will compel Washington to do its job."(4)
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Daschle</b></h2>
	Sen. Daschle deserves special status as a decoy--he led the charge against the Balanced Budget Amendment in 1995.  This is ironic considering that, like the others, he voted for the BBA in 1994 and in 1986 he ran a campaign ad declaring that when he first came to the Senate, "his first official act was to sponsor a constitutional amendment to balance the budget."  As is the case with others in Congress, perhaps the influence of Washington has caused him to listen to interests other than his constituents'.  Looking back on the failure of the BBA, Sen. Daschle smirked, "We had a good week."
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Bingaman</b></h2>
	Sen. Bingaman voted yes on the BBA in 1994 in anticipation of a difficult reelection campaign.  After winning reelection to another six-year term in November, 1994, Sen. Bingaman apparently decided he could safely abandon his election year conversion to the BBA.
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Dorgan</b></h2>
	Democrats fought the Balanced Budget Amendment last year with the claim that it would end up hurting the Social Security trust fund.  But all six Senators voted for the same amendment a year earlier.  At that time, Sen. Dorgan even disputed White House claims that the amendment would harm Social Security, saying, "the White House is not serving anyone's interests with these scare tactics on the balanced budget amendment."(5)
<p>
<p>
<h2><b>Conclusion</b></h2>
	The bottom line is that if even one of these decoy Senators had voted "yes" in 1995, as they had all voted only a year before, the Balanced Budget Amendment would now be before the state legislatures for ratification.
<p>
<p>
_________<br>
(1)   Larry King Live, CNN, October 6, 1994.<br>
(2)   Lambro, Donald, Commentary, Washington Times, p. A19, March 9, 1995.<br>
(3)   Pekkanen, Sarah, "Thurmond Says Balanced Budget Amendment Needed to Control Congress", States News Service, February 16, 1994.<br>
(4)   Lambro, note 2.<br>
(5)   Dorgan Press Release, "Dorgan Disputes White House Report on Balanced Budget Amendment", February 18, 1994, Federal Document Clearing House.<br>
<p>











