<html>
<head>
<title>Why did AFL-CIO chief George Meany help Warren Carroll...</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" 
align="left" ISMAP></a>
<center><h2>Culture Watch</h2></center>
<BR>
<center><h2>Why did AFL-CIO chief George Meany help Warren Carroll 
found Christendom College in Virginia's Shenandoah Valley?</h2><BR>
</center>
<center><h3>by Ann Marie Temple</h3></center>
<blockquote>
<p>Warren Carroll may be the most successful 
man in Virginia for he is one of the lucky 
few who can say that he is doing what he 
believes in every day of his life. 
Carroll is the founding president of Christendom College, 
a small liberal arts college tucked away in 
Virginia's picturesque Shenandoah Valley. Ten years ago 
he resigned his office to teach history full time at 
the college. He is an author and editor of numerous 
histories and biographies, including two books on 
the origin and history of the Communist Revolution 
and a newsletter tracking international resistance to 
communist insurgency.  He is currently at work on a 
multi-volume history of Western Civilization.  Many 
professors today view the past as a complex web of events that require periodic reinterpretion to fit 
current politically correct doctrines. But unlike 
most modern historians, Carroll teaches that 
individuals, not economic or social forces, are the shapers of 
history.  During the 1960s Carroll saw the Western 
tradition systematically abandoned as his fellow 
historians revised the past.  He concluded the only 
hope for a renaissance lay in America's youth. In 
1977, Carroll decided to change how history was 
taught by making history himself. He founded 
Christendom College.
<p>
Carroll insists history majors at Christendom
take at least one class on the history of 
revolutionary movements, either the French <BR>
Revolution or the Communist 
Revolution, and encourages his students to read 
<I>Witness</I>, the autobiography of Whitaker Chambers. It was after 
reading this book as a graduate student in 1954 that 
Carroll became a dedicated anti-communist. Carroll 
graduated from Bates College and received his doctorate 
in history from Columbia University. He is a 
prolific writer: in addition to two books on the Russian 
revolution, <I>1917</I> (Christendom Press, 1981) and 
<I>70 Years of the Communist Revolution</I> (republished as 
<I>The Rise and Fall of the Communist 
Revolution</I>, Christendom Press, 1995), Carroll established the 
<I>Freedom Fighter</I> newsletter to track &quot;counter-revolutionary&quot; 
activity throughout the world.  From 1985-1990, this 
publication covered the Afghan resistance, the 
Nicaraguan freedom fighters, and African anti-communist 
movements.  Carroll believes the revolutionary 
impulse remains alive and will continue to cause conflict. 
He thinks the best response is a strong defense of 
the Western tradition. He recently completed <I>The 
Last Crusade</I> (Christendom Press, 1996), a book 
about 1936, the first year of the Spanish Civil War.  

<BR>
Carroll has always been politically and socially
conservative. However, he arrived at a new perspective
after 1968.  He came to understand that modern 
societies were the battleground for the conflict between those who 
recognize objective realityand those committed to skepticism and 
moral relativism.  In 1967 Carroll was working in California politics 
and was not religious.  &quot;Technically, I was a Deist,&quot; he says. Then 
he married Anne Westhoff, a devout Catholic whom he met in 1962.  
 In 1968, the United States was facing what Carroll considers 
its greatest internal turmoil since the Civil War.  He calls the era 
a &quot;wild saturnalia&quot; and &quot;the height of the revolutionary 
movement, the rejection of all values and principles.&quot;  That year he 
converted to Catholicism and it became the key event in his life. The 
Carrolls moved to Washington in 1970.  His wife Anne began working 
for <I>Triumph</I>, a conservative Catholic magazine founded by 
Brent Bozell, William F. Buckley, Jr.'s brother-in-law. In 1973 
Carroll left politics and joined Anne at the magazine. 
<P>
<P><I>Triumph</I> hosted an annual six week summer institute at the 
Escorial, Philip II's palace outside Madrid.  The summer 
program was designed to introduce American students to the 
traditional liberal arts (history, literature, philosophy, political 
science, theology) in the physical context of a conservative and 
religious civilization.  Carroll taught American students in the Spanish 
program.  There, the &quot;person around whom all else revolved&quot; was 
Dr. Frederick Wilhelmsen, professor of philosophy and political 
science at the University of Dallas. In 1956, while teaching at 
UCLA, Wilhelmsen had organized 2,000 students to go to the aid of 
the Hungarian freedom fighters.  (They were stopped at the Los 
Angeles airport by authorities.)  Wilhelmsen was a strong influence 
on Carroll as he developed the curriculum of  the  new college.  
Teachers and students in the <I>Triumph</I> program in Spain eventually made 
up the nucleus of Christendom College.  
<P>
<P>With <I>Triumph</I>'s demise in 1975, Carroll decided to found 
a college that would emulate medieval universities 
by reinforcing the traditions of Western Civilization. 
Students at Christendom major in one of the traditional 
liberal arts:  English, Philosophy, Theology, Political Science, 
History, French, or Classical Languages.  All students must complete a 
core curriculum, including Christian doctrine, moral theology, and 
several semesters of philosophy.   By the 60's and 70's many 
American Catholic colleges had weakened their religious identity.  
Carroll saw a need for a college that would be uncompromisingly 
Catholic. And so as <I>Triumph</I> published its last issue in the summer 
of 1975, Carroll began making plans.  Thomas Aquinas College 
in Santa Paula, California, had been founded a few years earlier  
but Carroll thought more was needed: &quot;Bad as things had become, 
I was sure that a country as big as this could support at least 
two, especially on opposite sides of the country.&quot;  Money seemed to 
be the greatest obstacle. <I> </I>In order to maintain its 
independence, Christendom College does not receive money from the 
Church, although the Arlington, Virginia diocese is supportive and 
provides a chaplain.  Carroll likewise refused federal funding, 
even student loans. The college has grown with the support of  
loyal donors and benefactors among the Catholic laity.  As time 
has passed, money has not proved to be the main problem, 
and Christendom recently raised funds to build a new common 
room and chapel.   &quot;We always had more people who wanted to teach 
at Christendom College than we had places,&quot; says Carroll. Dr. 
Jeffrey Mirus, who wrote for <I>Triumph</I> and later taught history 
and literature as one of Christendom's founding faculty, says he 
was always struck by Carroll's ability &quot;to keep his eye on the goal.&quot; 
 Carroll was amazed to discover that his real challenge was 
finding students who saw the value of a classical education.  He had 
decided he would not start the college unless he had 25 initial 
applicants; he found 26.  But even finding pupils became easier, 
especially after the college received accreditation in 1986. Last year the 
 the college enrolled some 200 students.
<P>Admissions are selective, and the college is on the John 
Templeton honor role and has the highest rank from 
the Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement 
of Teaching.  Students come from all over the U.S, and 
from Canada, Mexico, Costa Rica, Hungary, and  Ireland.  All 
of the professors are practicing Catholics and make a 
yearly declaration of loyalty to the teachings of the Church.  
The school has a midnight curfew and a strict dress code 
(shirts and ties for men, knee-length skirts or business pants 
for women), along with sanctions against alcohol in 
student rooms and intervisitation between men's and women's 
dormitories.  These rules are enforced by older students 
appointed as  Resident Assistants under the direction of a 
Dean of Students.  Many applicants are frightened away 
by Christendom's strict rules, high standards and small 
size, but students consider  these to be advantages. The key 
social event of the year is the St. Patrick's Day party, 
with traditional Irish music and dancing performed by 
teachers, students, alumni, and even children of alumni.  Senior 
Cary McCoy says, &quot;It's like a big family event.  All the 
alumni come and everyone is eating and singing together.  
Dr. Carroll gets up and sings and everybody cheers.&quot;  
Graduate Lorraine Overbeck comments, &quot;Christendom is the 
only place where I can leave my purse in the cafeteria, 
come back a day later and find it where I left it with 
everything still in it.&quot;  
<P>
<P>Christendom's first classes were held in temporary class
rooms in Triangle, Virginia leased to Carroll by the
local Catholic parish.  Carroll had no idea where 
to move his college but had faith that God would send a 
solution.  His prayers were answered.  
<I>Triumph</I> had held a final weekend seminar in a lodge on the Shenandoah River 
owned by the AFL-CIO  and used for training Latin American 
labor organizers.  The manager was a friend of the magazine. 
 In 1979, the AFL-CIO decided to sell the property, but 
the asking price was too high for Carroll. Miraculously, the 
retired Patrick Cardinal O'Boyle was able to help.  
O'Boyle was a friend of George Meany, longtime AFL-CIO 
president.  The Cardinal persuaded Meany to lower the price 
by more than one third. After contacting a long list of 
prominent Catholics and friends of <I>Triumph</I>,  enough money 
was raised for the down payment.  Christendom College 
permanently relocated  in Front Royal, Virginia, 60 miles west 
of Washington. 
<P>
<P>Carroll considers his determination to be the legacy of
his earliest ancestor in America,  Englishman James 
Warren, who was captured at the battle of Dunbar 
fighting for King Charles II against Oliver Cromwell.  
Warren was shipped off to America as an indentured servant 
and obtained land in Maine. Carroll's ancestral home is on 
the site of the original &quot;Warren Garrison.&quot;   Carroll's 
great-grandfather, Robert Carroll was killed in the Civil War 
fighting for the Union at the Battle of Cedar Creek in 1864, 
a few miles from Christendom College. Like his battling 
Yankee ancestors, Christendom's founder has committed 
his lifetime to fighting -- this time on the side of  Catholic 
tradition. Today he lives and writes in Manassas, teaching 
a full load of history courses in Front Royal.  All his 
classes rest on the premise that history is the story of people.  
&quot;All this talk about trends and forces and so on . . . doesn't 
make any sense; these things are not real, they're 
imaginative themes.  People are the great reality in history and they 
are the ones who make it.&quot;  Carroll himself has 
demonstrated by his own actions that he is one of those people.
<P>
<P><I>[Warren Carroll can be reached at Christendom 
College, 134 Christendom Drive, Front Royal, VA 22530. 
Telephone (800) 877-5456, or on the web at 
http://www.crnet.org/christdm.htm]</I><BR>
</blockquote>
</BODY>
