<blockquote>
<center><img src="/crc/images/hdr-pcs.gif" alt="Philanthropy, Culture & Society"></center>
<P>
<b><i>September, 1996</i></b>
<h2>Exodus Youth Services<br>
</h2>
<h3>A Festival of Hope</h3>
<p>
<b>By Connie Marshner</b>
<p>
<a href="#poor">The Poorest of the Poor</a><BR>
<a href="#pics">The Pictures Tell the Stories</a><BR>
<a href="#logan">Logan and Mary Lyman Jackson</a><BR>
<a href="#called">Called by God</a><BR>
<a href="#langston">Langston Terrace Clean-up</a><BR>

<blockquote><i>
Connie Marshner is an administrator at Christendom College in Front Royal, Virginia.  Her last article for PCS was "Love Never Fails" in May 1995.</blockquote></i>
<P>
<dd>&quot;Don't go anywhere alone.  Always take somebody 
with you when you're walking in the neighborhood.  We'll 
have bathrooms in the Boys and Girls club.  You can use them 
at lunchtime.  Don't go into anybody's apartment.&quot;  Mary 
Lyman Jackson, a small woman with a marked southern 
accent, wearing jeans and a t-shirt is addressing her troops. It's 
a muggy summer morning in Washington D.C. and a 
hundred volunteers have turned out for  one of Exodus Youth 
Services' urban clean-up days. Mary thanks everyone for coming, 
and assures them that, despite the ominous sound of the 
liability release forms, nothing bad is going to happen.  &quot;These 
people are my friends,&quot;  she shouts, &quot;they're my family.  They love 
us, and they'll welcome us.  They're really looking forward to 
our coming.  This is a high spot in the year for them.&quot;
<dd>She introduces a priest, who reads the gospel from 
yesterday's Feast of Saints Peter and Paul, then raises his hands in 
blessing over the assembled group, sprinkling them with holy water 
in the name of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit.  She 
urges people to car pool because parking is scarce where they 
are going.  In that amazing process by which confusion 
becomes order, in five minutes everybody is in a van, and a 
procession of vehicles pulls out of the parking lot, following 
&quot;Streetside,&quot; an enormous RV with a garish design on its side.
<dd>The Festival of Hope, 1996, for Langston Terrace 
has begun.  Exodus Youth Ministries is in full swing.  
<P>
<P><CENTER>*   *   *</CENTER><BR>
<dd>An exodus is usually about leaving.  This Exodus is all 
about entering:   Exodus Youth Services Inc. enters the inner city 
of Washington, D.C., that the people may go forth out of 
slavery and into the promised land.   Every Tuesday, Thursday, 
and Friday night since 1987, Streetside has been driven through 
the streets of Washington, D.C. Once parked it is a staging 
ground from which Exodus volunteers talk about God's love and 
help local residents find in Him freedom from the slavery of 
poverty and drugs and violence.  
<dd>&quot;We're an ecumenical Catholic ministry serving the 
poorest of the poor in the Nation's Capital,&quot; says Mary Lyman 
Jackson, 39, the President of Exodus and widow of its founder, 
Rev. K. Logan Jackson.  &quot;We're a 50l(c)(3) [nonprofit], 
incorporated under the laws of the District of Columbia, and we 
focus on serving children and families in the metropolitan 
Washington area, particularly the homeless, runaways, latchkey 
children, and refugees.  Our main mission is to bring the gospel 
of Our Lord Jesus Christ to the poor so they come to know 
Him as their personal Lord and Savior, and then get them into a 
local church.&quot;
<dd>During the eleven years that Exodus has existed, 
seminarians from every denomination with a theological school in 
the nation's capital have done internships or volunteered 
with Exodus Youth Ministries. They have overcome their 
own fears, and learned to love.  One year, Logan Jackson received Goodwill Industries of America's Edgar J. Helms Award 
for outstanding service.  In 1990, Logan was honored by 
<I>Washingtonian</I> magazine as &quot;Washingtonian of the Year.&quot;    
<dd>Letters of appreciation and testimony about Exodus, 
from Episcopal, Lutheran, Catholic, Moravian, and 
non-denominational seminarians fill the ministry files. All have learned 
from Exodus.
<dd>Not all the letters of endorsement are from religious 
organizations and leaders.  Edwin J. Feulner, President of the 
Heritage Foundation, describes himself as &quot;increasingly 
enthusiastic about its ministry.&quot;  <I>Dallas Morning 
News</I> columnist William Murchison has written that Mary Lyman Jackson 
&quot;is entitled to that special awe attending what our sad, 
sordid world accounts sacrifice.&quot;  
<P>
<P><a name="poor">
<B>The Poorest of the Poor</B><p>
<dd>Exodus has written a Streetside Catechism, which aims 
to teach the truths of the Catholic Faith, based on Scripture, 
the Catechism of the Catholic Church, and the lives of the saints. 
 It is geared toward the illiterate and marginalized.  It 
targets everyone older than two years of age.  Written by two 
professors of theology, one at Catholic University and one at 
the Franciscan University of Steubenville, it awaits an 
<I>Imprimatur</I> from Cardinal Hickey, and it will then be distributed 
nationwide. 
<dd>Another Exodus publication is the &quot;Streetside 
Epistles.&quot; These are weekly letters of hope that evangelize 
residents without telephones that the van doesn't get to visit.
<dd>Right now, Exodus is working with over 4000 individuals 
in five neighborhoods: Langston Terrace NE, Adams 
Morgan NW, Morton Street/Georgia Avenue NW, Potomac 
Gardens SE, and Stanton Dwellings SE.  These are areas 
largely forgotten by the rest of the world, with the exception of 
Adams Morgan, a diverse neighborhood with many trendy 
African and Caribbean restaurants.  
<dd>&quot;The only hassling we ever get is from tourists in 
Adams-Morgan, who don't want to see the poor,&quot; says Mary Lyman. 
 &quot;They just want an exotic dinner.  Druggies don't bother us. 
 Usually they come and ask us to pray for them.  There was 
one who was the drug lord in a neighborhood.  He'd jump start 
the van whenever it needed it.  He didn't want us to pray 
for him...once I ran half a block after him, yelling at him to 
hold still so I could pray for him....  He protected us fine.  He's in 
jail now for bouncing checks.&quot; 
<dd>When your clients are so far down that the drug lords feel 
protective of them, you know you are working with the poorest 
of the poor. These are the ones who fall through the cracks of 
other systems, the ones who are &quot;unreachable&quot; and unreached, 
the ones whose problems are so overwhelming that no 
bureaucrat would touch them.  
<dd>The District of Columbia is bankrupt;  these days one 
cannot even be sure that the trash will  be picked up, let alone any 
more sophisticated service performed.  Back in 1986, the D.C. Task 
Force on Runaway and Homeless Youth admitted that &quot;No real 
`system' of services to runaway and homeless youth currently exists. . . 
Services are neither coordinated, consistently available nor easily 
available to those who need them.&quot; And things have only gotten 
worse since then.
<dd>But Exodus gets help where it can. When necessary it 
works with other agencies and ministries in the Washington area 
for referrals and outreach, food, clothing, furniture, shelter, 
job placement and training, emergency groceries and rent, funerals, adoptions, physical and mental health care, and dentistry.
<P>
<P><a name="pics">
<B>The Pictures Tell the Stories</B><p>
<dd>Logan Jackson incorporated the ministry in 1986 and 
with a large grant from the Bingham Foundation of Louisville 
he bought &quot;Streetside,&quot; a large recreational vehicle.  
Originally, the vehicle had &quot;Health Screening and Referrals&quot; printed on 
its side, as Exodus had doctors travelling with its 
volunteers, looking to physical needs while they tended to the soul. 
But Exodus got out of the healthcare business when the 
D.C. Government started something similar.
<dd>The Exodus home office is a rented old frame house 
in suburban Maryland, perhaps one of the summer 
cottages which constituted Old Town Gaithersburg a hundred 
years ago.  It is worn, and the floors are bare, but it is neat and clean. 
 While I was there, a truck pulled up with lawnmowers, and 
a crew of teenage boys began to mow the lawn.  Mary 
Lyman knows them by their first names; they are from a 
landscape company owned by a friend.  Is the work done 
<I>pro bono</I> or for pay?  &quot;I don't know,&quot; she says absently. &quot;I forget what 
the arrangement is this summer.&quot;   Her attention is on the 
pictures that line the walls of the staircase--pictures of Exodus 
volunteers helping kids with arts and crafts, doing puppet shows, 
standing with arms around people, praying.  Sometimes Mary 
Lyman calls it &quot;friendship evangelism.&quot;  
<dd>The pictures often tell harrowing stories. &quot;That boy sitting 
in the Greyhound bus was a refugee.  He had come across 
the border with his dad in a cattle car and gotten separated,&quot; 
Mary Lyman told me.  &quot;Somehow the boy had wandered all the way 
to Washington alone; and one night, speaking no English, he 
walked up to our great big RV.  Exodus found his dad; the picture 
was taken as he was leaving D.C. on his way back to him.&quot;
<dd>The two sullen-looking punks are upper-middle class runaways. 
 &quot;Lots of it is peer pressure, but a lot of it is because of 
emotional abuse.  It's not a political statement, it's an actual way of life.  Once they get on the street, 
they get into prostitution, drug trafficking...  Their life 
expectancy is three years....   If there isn't an intervention within the 
first weeks on the street, they develop neuroses from the 
pressure, the lack of sleep, lack of nourishment, despair.  
They're exposed to things they've never seen before.  They get 
STDs too.&quot; 
<dd>There's an eviction scene, a small boy's face distorted with grief as he watches 
his kitten being taken away by an Animal Control warden.
<dd>There's a bed, shoved into a corner between two dirty walls.  The bed is 
piled high with crumpled laundry.  &quot;Sometimes they just wear clothes until they're too dirty, then they 
go down and get more, because they can't afford the soap 
and laundry expenses.&quot;  Does Exodus give away clothing?  
&quot;We have in the past, but not now.  They can go other places to 
get it for free.&quot;
<dd>A bearded man, with a child in a backpack, looks straight 
out at the camera.  &quot;He was a contractor, but his clients didn't 
pay up, so he lost his house.  He lived out of his car, with his six 
kids and pregnant wife ....  
<dd>&quot;If families go into shelters, the shelters will split up 
the husbands and wives.  There was a case in '88, a woman had 
left an abusive husband, and she and her kids were in the 
welfare hotel with  300 other kids.  We got her into counseling.  
We went to court to get her custody of those kids.  Exodus 
had arranged for a Christian transitional living arrangement 
in Virginia.  The day before the court date, D.C. welfare took 
her kids away from her....  She was suicidal....&quot;
<dd>When Exodus is involved in cases of abuse, they find 
the mother and children a safe place, arrange for medical care 
and emergency money, find psychological support, and then 
a home in Washington, Maryland or Virginia.  &quot;We have 
quite a network,&quot; Mary Lyman smiles.  
<dd>There is a picture of two little girls, toddlers, on a 
bare mattress. &quot;Their mom has HIV, and according to her 
will, when she dies, those girls will be mine.&quot;
<dd>A picture of a little girl with an eager expression on her face. 
 &quot;She was left toddling in a stairwell when she was two. 
 Nobody ever saw her mother again.&quot;  
<dd>&quot;We're child advocates.  We go to local police, courts, 
and so on, on behalf of children when no one else will.  We do 
the same type of work as a guardian <I>ad litem 
</I>in court proceedings.  There was a 17-year old boy who had a heart attack, and he 
was diabetic.  He was at Greater Southeast Hospital, which is 
not where you'd want to be with that problem.  Children's 
Hospital has a much better cardiology unit.  I talked to more people 
than I can remember to get it arranged so he could be transferred....&quot;
<dd>There are pictures of young adults sharing their faith 
with street youths; a young man earnestly talking with four 
toddlers on a streetcorner.  &quot;When the children come to the van, 
we make the sign of the cross on their forehead in oil, seal them 
in the sign of the cross, and tell them `You belong to God, 
you have dignity as a child of God.'  They line up to be prayed 
with, even the Muslims.  They begin to know that God loves them. 
<dd>&quot;We started out being good-works oriented.  And then 
the Lord really showed us that the needs of these people were 
so drastic, the only thing that would really work is Jesus.  Jesus 
is the way of rescuing them from the kingdom of darkness....  
Our primary focus is spiritual, to bring them to Jesus, to 
incorporate them into the Body of Christ, to disciple them and help 
them give their lives to the Lord.&quot; But doing that cannot be 
separated from the work of meeting the material, medical, and 
physical needs of the people.
<dd>In the waiting room and office--once a living 
room--a large framed poster proclaims in bright primary colors 
the names of God: &quot;And thou shalt call His name Jesus, Prince 
of Peace, Mighty God, Wonderful Counselor, Holy One, 
Lamb of God...&quot;
<dd>There is also a picture of Logan Jackson, the founder 
of Exodus Ministries, on a sidewalk next to Streetside, in 
a wheelchair with a headrest, surrounded by street people. 
<dd>Logan had Lou Gehrig's disease, and he progressively 
lost the use of his entire body.  At the time that picture was 
taken he could not even move his head and could speak only in 
a whisper, but he was there praying with them and 
encouraging them.  Mary Lyman nursed him around the clock for 
ten months before he died.  &quot;When you have that disease, 
ultimately you die of suffocation, which is how Jesus is thought to 
 have died on the cross.  He had a very special relationship 
with Jesus, but especially at the end.&quot;  The end came for Logan 
on June 9, 1993.  His wife, Mary Lyman, had been named head 
of the ministry by its board of directors in 1990. 
<P>
<P><a name="logan">
<B>Logan and Mary Lyman Jackson</B><p>
<dd>While Exodus was still recovering from the strain of 
Logan's illness and death,  his 17-year old son, Mercer Jackson, 
almost died. On February 10, 1995 Mercer was in a car accident 
that broke his cheekbone, eye socket, jaw, shoulders, wrist,  
leg, and every rib.  Before the accident, two colleges had 
offered Mercer lacrosse scholarships.  It took a long time for him 
to recover, and it hit the family hard.  But the ministry rolled 
with the punches.  &quot;Everybody helped out,&quot; says Mary Lyman.  
A friend, John Boughton, who had been running a ministry 
in Bosnia, was visiting at the time.  He cancelled his return 
to Bosnia to temporarily take charge of Exodus.  A team of 
girls recently graduated from the Franciscan University 
of Steubenville were doing some missionary work with 
Exodus at the time, and they stayed on.  Volunteers abounded, and 
the work continued.
<dd>Mercer is back in school again, John Boughton has gone 
on to seminary, and Mary Lyman runs the ministry from her 
home and the office.
<dd>Eileen Jones, director of Streetside, marvels at how well 
the system works.  &quot;No matter where Mary Lyman is, that's 
where the phone rings.  If she's home, the phone rings there; if 
she's here, it rings here.  She doesn't tell people where she's 
going to be, they just seem to know.&quot;  Mary Lyman has a beeper, 
and the people on the street have her numbers.  They call her 
to encourage her sometimes.  But they usually call to ask for help. 
<dd>During Logan's illness, neither Logan nor Mary Lyman 
had time for fundraising and money became tight.  They 
didn't know where the next dime would come from.  But it seems 
as though that experience confirmed God's pleasure with 
the ministry.
<dd>&quot;We had a George Mueller experience,&quot;  Mary 
explains. &quot;He started orphanages in England in the 1800s, and he 
wasn't much at asking for money.  He would pray and pray and 
pray, and orphans would come in the thousands.  He would pray 
and pray, for days sometimes, and then the money would come in. 
 So from March to June, 1990, we prayed and prayed, and 
we literally received checks to the penny for everything 
the ministry needed.  Volunteers kept coming and the 
ministry went through a spiritual transformation.  We became 
explicitly Christian rather than interfaith, which was how we 
started out.&quot;  
<dd>The ministry's total revenues for 1994 were $136,016; 
for 1995, $173,501.   Currently, Exodus has two paid staff 
positions. Eileen Jones, director of Streetside, fills one of them 
and there's an opening for an administrative assistant. The 
ministry has 30 regular volunteers. Several thousand others, if 
you count the schools, civic organizations, and parishes that 
help with special projects pitch in over the course of a year.   
And then there are the volunteers in the neighborhoods and on 
the streets.  They contribute a significant part of the work to 
events like the Festival of Hope in Langston Terrace.  Big days 
like that are organized in every season.  
<dd>Two teachers from a school a half hour away came by 
the office during this reporter's visit.  They celebrated the end of the school year, and carried in boxes of mustard and mayonnaise packets, sodas leftover from the teachers' party, and 
a few plastic bags with clothes--items the kids never 
claimed from Lost and Found all year, they said, sort of sheepishly. 
 Obviously, they had been to Exodus  before.  They're 
probably in the category of friends, rather than volunteers. No 
one registered the items when they left.  They were not logged 
in. It is possible that Exodus might have more volunteers than 
it realizes.  
<dd>Occasionally, Exodus has had involuntary volunteers, 
people referred by courts to do mandatory community service.  
&quot;We had a Congressman once.  Then there was this skinhead 
who was assigned to us by a judge.  He sat in the office for three 
days and didn't say a word.  We prayed with him most of those 
three days, and after that, he opened up and told us his story of abuse. 
 When the community service was finished, he stayed on as 
a volunteer.&quot; 
<dd>Still, there is the need for money.  The rent has to be 
paid, gasoline has to be bought, repairs must be completed, the grass must be mowed. 
 Where does it come from?  Exodus is in the Combined Federal Campaign 
and the Catholic Network of Volunteers.  According to its audit report, 
contributions make up the lion's share of revenues, with in-kind donations 
adding about 25%.  The donations come from individuals, corporations, and 
foundations.  Exodus maintains a house list, and about once 
every quarter, it sends out fundraising letters.  They bring results,  
but it's not a top priority:  &quot;If we're supposed to be doing a 
letter, and someone dies, we do the funeral instead,&quot; says 
Mary Lyman.  
<dd>The books show contributions from corporations like 
Phillip Morris and Hechingers, a chain of super-hardware stores in 
the Washington area.  There are lots and lots of in-kind 
contributions, of course.  And some foundations such as the 
Abell Foundation and the George E. Coleman Jr. Foundation 
also contribute.
<dd>Mary Lyman gets restless talking finances.  &quot;I can be 
a businesswoman, or I can be an evangelist,&quot; she says.  &quot;If I 
talk like a businesswoman,  I can tell you we'll come close to 
our projected budget.  We could do a business analysis, but it's 
not going to mean beans, because that's not how God works. 
 When I talk as an evangelist, I can tell you that this ministry 
has survived not on human cleverness but on God's providence.  
If God wants us to expand, He sends us a little more; if He wants us to 
cut back, He sends us a little less.&quot;
<dd>Yes, she knows that there are professional ways, proven ways of 
raising money.  &quot;I try to do it,&quot; she acknowledges.  &quot;But it's not 
systematic.  We don't have a full-time Director of Development.  We 
have volunteers.  I'll get a phone call, with someone recommending I go 
visit someone.  And nine times out of ten, when I meet with corporate 
executives, they give us money.  But I'm not making a concerted effort at it.  
I fit it in.  If I did it, we'd probably have a lot of money.  But the way 
it works, when there have been things I've felt the Lord wanted us to do, 
the money comes.  And when there are ideas, and I'm not sure God wants 
us to do them, then he holds back the money.  The unique thing about us 
is that we pray for the funds.&quot; 
<P>
<P><a name="called">
<B>Called By God</B><p>
<dd>While praying for funds is unusual,  the ministry's 
beginnings were unique as well.  
<dd> Logan Jackson was a quiet man, a gentle priest at St. James 
 Episcopal outside Louisville.  At the seminary, he had 
been known to his classmates as a conservative. In the diocese 
he was known in the same way--as someone not prone to 
flights of fancy. 
<dd>His wife, Mary Lyman was living on a five-acre horse 
farm, busy with three babies, ten Welsh Corgis, and her career as 
a concert pianist, when Logan heard God telling him in 
prayer that he should leave everything and seek first His kingdom 
by helping children. The only other time Logan had ever 
heard from the Lord so clearly was in his calling to be a priest.  
<dd>They could tell that God was softening their hearts.  And 
so they left, not knowing where they were headed.  
Logan's bishop,  however, thought it was their heads that had gone 
soft and offered to pay for psychiatric counseling.  Their 
families thought the bishop's offer should be considered.
<dd>But the Jacksons  were determined. They put their 
belongings in storage and lived in an abandoned Anglican convent 
in Tennessee for six months while Logan travelled around, 
visiting such places as Covenant House in New York City, 
the Seattle Rape Center, and Boston's Bridge Over 
Troubled Waters.  It was there that he conceived the idea of the 
&quot;Streetside&quot; van, and along the way, God told him Washington, D.C. 
was where He wanted him.  So they moved into the city, 
and initially ministered from their home. Logan would bring 
the street to their house, and Mary Lyman would teach.
<dd>They had an office in a rundown neighborhood in 
Washington, but after a while they learned it wasn't realistic to 
expect the poor to come to them.  It was a better use of time and 
money to go directly to the poor.  When they found out that Logan 
was dying, they moved out of the city to Gaithersburg--a suburb 
at the end of the Washington Metrorail  system.  It was 
cheaper, and it seemed a better place to be.  Along the way, each 
member of the family had spontaneously been drawn to 
Catholicism, and they converted as a family in 1992.  For Logan, it was 
in no way a rejection of his Episcopalian identity, but rather 
a fulfillment of it, a way to experience closer communion 
with the Lord whose sufferings he was already sharing in his body. 
<P>
<P><a name="langston">
<B>Langston Terrace Clean-up</B><p>
<dd>A  short drive down North Capitol Street and across H 
Street brings the caravan of vehicles to Langston Terrace, the 
nation's oldest public housing development.  It contains 308 units.  
The three-story flat-roof brick buildings are somewhat 
overgrown with nondescript shrubs, and the playground features 
socialist-realist concrete sculptures and is uninviting. But the place 
is not as littered with trash as it used to be.  Mary Lyman 
offers the explanation that Exodus has been coming here 
regularly for eight years, and you can see in the neighborhood what 
is reflected in the hearts and minds of the residents:  &quot;If you 
know you're worth something, you want your environment to 
look like something.&quot;
<dd>At ten o'clock in the morning the streets are for the 
moment bereft of people.  Exodus has come for a Festival of Hope. 
The day will include free food, landscaping services, and 
activities for neighborhood residents and their children. Teams 
assemble and orders are given.  Blue, Red, Green, Peach, 
and Black teams line up to unload plants from the 
heavily-laden Streetsideit takes a good twenty minutes to do the job.
<dd>A local politician strolls up to try to wheedle some 
landscaping services for Carver Terrace, which adjoins Langston. 
&quot;I'm from the Mayor's office,&quot; he says in a tone of intimacy which 
he expects to bring results.  Mary Lyman comes out of the van 
to negotiate. She explains why she can't oblige him.  In the end, 
she hands him a flat of impatiens, and he leaves happy.  &quot;These 
people are my family, they'd kill me if I didn't keep my word.&quot;    
Obviously she is familiar with the ways of local politicians.
<dd>The landscaping teams start raking through grass that hasn't been cut all summer, and around rusted chain link fences rolled around their posts.  It would have been easy to remove 
the useless chain link, but it required a tool that no one had. 
There's lots of broken glass, but surprisingly few cigarette butts. 
Two local boys, maybe seven or eight years old, ask if they can help. 
 A few mothers emerge from the buildings to go to the 
mailboxes, then disappear again.  A teenage boy and his 
little brother, maybe eight years old, leave an apartment building, the big brother 
adjusting a key on a chain around the neck of his sibling.  They separate as they 
go down the sidewalk, away from the people who have come to clean up their 
neighborhood.
<dd>The work continues.  Mary Lyman distributes shovels, with a warning 
&quot;Don't let anybody get hold of them but you.  We'll never see them again.&quot;  A 
local man who runs a rehab program teaching landscaping skills to ex-prisoners 
arrives with his truck, on which are lawnmowers and edgers.  
The power tools are manned by a volunteer skilled in 
operating such equipment and an older man, who drove a van of 
young folks down from New Jersey for the day.
<dd>A priest working with Exodus is on the sidewalk, 
praying with three women.  Janice McCree, the President of the 
local Residents' Council, leads a volunteer team leader to the Council's offices, which are to be painted that afternoon.  
The Council is in the basement of a building, through a 
padlocked steel grate door.  There are two air conditioners in the 
offices, which run the length of the basement.  One doesn't work at 
all, the other works well, but it drains inside rather than out.  
A steady stream of water drips down the wall and puddles on 
the floor.  Later, when the wall has been painted, the water drips down 
through the fresh paint, and a milky-colored pool collects on the floor.  
<dd>Walking down the sidewalk with Janice is an experience.  She 
makes eye contact with everyone, no matter their age, and she knows their 
names. They all return the eye contact and speak respectfully to her.  
Janice says she has lived in Langston Terrace for 34 years.  Later in the 
day, she shows me pictures of her son's wedding.  He's a teacher at 
Towson State College in Maryland.  Her daughter is an entertainer, 
presently in Spain.  With a son and daughter on the road to  middle-class lives, 
why is she still living in Langston Terrace?  Her leadership and 
influence at Langston Terrace are answer enough.  
<dd>The basement of another building houses the Langston/Carver Case Management and 
Community Building Project, &quot;a collaborative effort of the 
Department of Health and Human Services and the D.C. 
Housing Authority,&quot; according to a posted flyer.  This basement 
is divided into smaller rooms, and features file cabinets 
and tables filled with AIDS/HIV information, and meeting 
announcements such as one for a baby care training 
evening sponsored jointly by Georgetown University and 
Children's Hospital.  Volunteers come through looking for a 
bathroom facility.  There is a toilet and sink, and they take turns 
holding the door closed for each other. There is no toilet 
paper, however, and no towels. 
<dd>During lunch break, the landscaping team carries 
their shovels to the courtyard and suddenly life seems to abound.  Children are all over the place.  Mothers stand in clumps.  
A few adult males have appeared.  &quot;The ones who are addicted 
to crack will be thin, so thin.  Their face will have a gray, 
pasty color to it.  They'll be standing around out of focus,&quot; 
Mary says.  Some match that description.  
<dd>Exodus has barbecue grills fired up on which are sizzling 
hot dogs and hamburgers for the residents.  But volunteers 
eat prepared sandwiches from long bread bags.  Enormous 
plastic bags of cut watermelon and trashcans filled with ice and sodas 
 round out the meal.  For forty minutes volunteers relax on 
steps and on the base of the 1940s concrete sculpture which some 
say is an elephant, some a mountain lion.  The feast for 
the residents continues through the afternoon, long after the 
volunteers have gone back to work.  The Yellow team starts up 
the arts and crafts program after lunch, manning the puppet stage. 
 The drama is the story of the Good Samaritan in street 
dialect, using animal hand puppets. 
<dd>The front yards of rowhouses comprise the sides of 
the courtyard.  Most are neglected, though a few show signs of 
past effortsa rose bush, or some planters.  Off to one corner of 
the courtyard, though, is a front lawn as green and tidy as any 
in a posh suburb.  A table is set up in front of the door, in the 
shade of a large tree, and a family--men and women and 
children--seem to be playing cards.  The children do not mingle 
with those running and screaming in the courtyard.  The adults 
seem to have their own food, their own entertainment.  One 
wonders what accounts for the difference.  That scene of 
domestic stability and contentment is probably close to the vision FDR had when he opened the Langston Terrace.  But unfortunately it is the exception.
<dd>Mary Lyman circulates through the crowds, speaking 
with everybody, greeting most by their first name, familiarly, 
comfortably.  Everybody knows her.  She gets smiles from 
everyone, as do the volunteers she's with.
<dd>&quot;The first time I went on the streets with my husband, 
God transformed me.  It was around Dupont Circle, and a 
homeless man was dying.  I was crying, I didn't know what to do, it 
was my first time.  The homeless guys put their hands on me and prayed over me.  I'd never heard speaking in tongues before.  But that day, my solidarity with the poor started.  The 
poor bring us Jesus.  We don't bring Jesus to them.  We pray, 
we catechize, we do the social worker stuff too.  But on that 
first night, I became their little sister.  I have learned so much 
from the poor, they have given me so much joy....&quot;<BR><BR>
<hr>
<CENTER><B>For more information contact:</b>
<P>
Exodus Youth Services
<br>P O Box 2398
<br>Gaithersburg, MD  20886-2398
<br>301-590-0155</CENTER>
</BODY>
