<head>
<title>Why did a reclusive widow...</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="0" align="left" ISMAP></A>
<center><h2>Culture Watch</h2></center>
<blockquote>
<center><h2>
Why Did a Reclusive Widow Give the Washington Opera Eighteen Million Dollars?
</h2></center>
<center><h3>by Shayna Cook</h3></center>
<p>
Betty Brown Casey surprised the nation's capital last March when she donated eighteen million dollars to buy the Woodward and Lothrop department store.  Casey made a gift of the magnificent downtown flagship of the now-bankrupt chain so that the building could be transformed into a world class Opera House by the year 2000.  Mrs. Casey attends the Opera regularly, and her hope is that the new facility will provide both "a world-class opera house in the nation's capital" and "a center for the musical arts that will be available to literally thousands of children in this community,"  according to an Opera spokeswoman. The new facility will seat 2,100 in its main theater and include offices, a rooftop restaurant, and space for its educational programs.  Livingston Biddle, President Carter's Chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts and longtime Opera Board member, praised Casey's move, describing the arts patron as "dedicated, committed to excellence in the arts, tenacious and bold."  Her lawyer Brendan Sullivan, who represented Oliver North in the Iran-Contra affair, says Mrs. Casey is "an extraordinary woman who possesses a strong character and an exceedingly generous heart."
<p>
Charitable and cultural contributions have consistently been Casey's personal concerns.  Preferring privacy to acclaim, she had maintained a low profile for years while giving millions to various charities in the Washington, D.C.  metropolitan area.  Her timing has been perfect. World-renowned tenor Placido Domingo was delighted to declare on his first day as Artistic Director, "It's really, really tremendous.  It is a wonderful decision and a great day for the Washington Opera."   Now the Opera will have to raise $100 million to complete the facility and chances look very good indeed. Attendance has averaged 98 percent over the last eleven seasons, and the Opera receives $4 million in private contributions annually from friends all around the world who have spent time in diplomatic assignments.  With the addition of Domingo (one of PBS's "Three Tenors") to the cast, demand for tickets has been unprecedented.  Domingo's singing, acting, and conducting make him "a true renaissance man in music," says Italy's Corriere della Sera newspaper. Newsweek called him "the King of Opera." Domingo has Opera in his blood. As a child he worked for his parents' opera  company in Mexico City.
<p>
This fall the star tenor will star in the Washington Opera's season opener: Antonio Carlos Gomes' Il Guarany, an Indian extravaganza directed by German film dirctor Werner Herzog (Aguirre, Wrath of God).  Excited at the new management and new repertorie, the Opera's education director Debra Blount declares Domingo "is the best ambassador for opera there is."  In a recent appearance on Conan O'Brien's late night television show, the enthusiastic and personable Domingo persuaded the entire studio audience to sing along with him.
<p>
Casey's own life has been in many ways as dramatic as one of Domingo's productions.  In 1955 she married Eugene B. Casey, a prominent New Deal Democrat who worked for Presidents Roosevelt and Truman and at one time owned more real estate than anyone in the United States. Surely she suffered from reminders that her husband went to jail for tax-evasion in 1946 (and was pardoned by President Truman in 1951). After her husband's death in 1986,  Casey endured her own personal ordeals, including a bomb planted in her Mercedes in 1990 as an attempt on her life and a bitter 1993 lawsuit from ten of her late husband's grandchildren from previous marriages over her inheritance.
<p>
Despite the Opera's obvious successes, it had to overcome opposition from the notoriously difficult D.C. government.  The city's Zoning Commission had restricted the use of the Woodies building to retail in order to generate tax revenues for the city.  Attracting business was a worthy objective, but two other department store buildings still remained empty  and downtown. One commissioner, Howard Croft,  protested the interjection of culture into a panhandler-ridden area of the city: "Art for whom? . . . Downtown [should be] for all the people who live in the metropolitan area."  Luckily for the Opera, Croft was defeated by a vote of 4 to 1 on July 1 when the Commission met and approved the building renovation. Officials at the Opera are quick to rebut Croft's contention that opera is elitist.  Opera deals with universal human themes of passion and suffering, and "every culture enjoys music and storytelling," spokeswoman Suzanne Stephens points out.  The field of Opera rewards musical and dramatic talents regardless of financial background.  In the words of executive director Patricia L. Mossel, opera "cuts across all economic and age barriers."  The Washington Opera makes its performances accessible through English surtitles and extensive community outreach programs.  Currently such programs reach 20,000 students in D.C., Virginia, and Maryland annually.With the new facility more students will be able to participate in Opera programs: from trying on costumes and waving a conductor's baton to meeting the performers and attending a performance.  On the verge of bankruptcy, DC schools are eliminating music and arts from their curriculum.  So, the Opera sends performers and docents to some of the district's poorest schools.  According to Blount, "the only negative comments we get from the children is that they wanted to see more."
<p>
Exposure to opera at such a yound age increases the odds that some of the children will grow to be opera fans.  Domingo contends that he can see young people in the audience from the stage, and is constantly searching for young potential artists: he sponsors a singing competition in Mexico City that seeks out fresh talent.  Domingo, described by Opera insiders as "the most accessible human being," is determined to keep the Washington Opera open to its DC neighbors.  He will personally make sure that tickets are distributed to the underprivileged.
<p>
And there is sure to be demand because in America today, the art form is thriving.  "There is an explosion of opera in the United States," Stephens says.  She vows that any non-fan can be converted, no matter how old they are: "My answer to them is to find the right opera."  And if the sell-out crowds provide any evidence, the Washington Opera has put on "the right opera" for many people.  The Opera operates purely though popular appeal to individual ticketholders and donors.  Unlike some European houses, the Washington Opera does not depend on public funds. It receives no subsidy from any state agency, and a $72,000 grant from the National Endowment for the Arts accounts for merely .017 percent of total contributed revenue.  The example of the Washington Opera has given the lie to  NEA lobbyists who claim cutting federal funding of the arts will undermine the survival of art itself.  According to Stephens, "The NEA has never been a large percentage of our budget . . .we have learned to go about surviving and thriving without it."  Thanks to the sterling example of Betty Brown Casey and the artistic brilliance of  Placido Domingo, the Washington Opera will do its part to help the nation's capital survive and thrive as well.
<p><BR>
<hr>
<FONT  SIZE=-1>The Washington Opera is (currently) located at the Kennedy Center, Washington, DC 20566, (202) 416-7890.</FONT>
</BODY>
