<P>
<i><FONT SIZE=4>April 1996<BR>
</FONT></B></i>
<h2><B><FONT SIZE=4>Welfare Reform in the States:<BR>
</FONT></B></h2>
<B>Part I</B><P>
<A HREF="#mich">Michigan: Have We Gone Far Enough?</A><BR>
<A HREF="#mass">Massachusetts: Why State-Level Reform Won't Work</A><BR>
<A HREF="#ind">Indiana: Reorientating Welfare</A><BR>
<A HREF="#wis">Wisconsin: Work Requirements for All Welfare Recipients</A><BR>
<A HREF="#colo">Colorado: An Agenda for the State Legislature</A><BR>
<A HREF="#washi">Washington I: Needed: A Strong Dose of Common Sense</A><BR>
<A HREF="#washii">Washington II: Dismantling the Welfare Culture</A><BR>


<P>
 Welfare reform is well under way in the states.  Despite President
Clinton's recent veto of welfare reform legislation, many states
have received or are seeking waivers from the federal government
to reform their welfare systems.  This issue presents contributions
by leaders of state public-policy think tanks.  It examines reforms
already made in six states and proposes new ideas to make charities
and nonprofit organizations key providers of private welfare services.
<P>
 Lawrence W. Reed, president of the Midland, Michigan-based Mackinac
Center for Public Policy, describes Michigan Governor John Engler's
ambitious welfare reforms.  He notes, however, that charities
must become more involved in these efforts.  David G. Tuerck,
executive director of Boston's Beacon Hill Institute, offers a
tax-credit proposal that would address Reed's concern.  It would
shift welfare responsibilities from government to charities.
<P>
 Three articles follow which emphasize the importance of moving
welfare recipients into the workforce.  Andrew Bush, a research
fellow and director of the Welfare Policy Center at the Indianapolis-based
Hudson Institute, argues that Indiana should adopt an aggressive
work-based welfare program.  Michael E. Hartmann, Director of
Research at the Milwaukee-based Wisconsin Policy Research Institute,
describes a strong workfare program likely to be signed into law
this month by Governor Tommy Thompson.  Tom Tancredo and Dwight
Filley, president and senior fellow, respectively, of the Golden,
Colorado-based Independence Institute, discuss the role of fatherlessness
in long-term welfare dependency and propose workfare and other
programs to address this problem.
<P>
 Two concluding articles from Washington state think tanks emphasize
why private efforts to help the needy are more likely to succeed
than government programs.  John Carlson, chairman of the Seattle's
Washington Institute for Policy Studies, uses a &quot;thought
experiment&quot; to outline principles that should be the basis
of any welfare reform effort.  Lynn Harsh and Bob Williams, executive
director and president, respectively, of the Olympia-based Evergreen
Freedom Foundation, discuss ways to implement some of these principles
in their state.
<P>
 Next month's issue will carry additional articles by state think
tank leaders on state-level welfare reform.
<P>
<B><A NAME="mich">Michigan: Have We Gone Far Enough?</A></B>
<P>
<B>by Lawrence W. Reed</B>
<P>
 Welfare programs may well be the most unpopular of all government
initiatives--criticized by social scientists who observe the results,
disdained by taxpayers who pay the bills, and often unloved by
many of those who collect the benefits.  Even the Maryland State
Conference of the NAACP says that welfare &quot;is a major contributory
factor to the crime problems we face today.&quot;  Unlike private
efforts that stress character-building, one-on-one mentoring and
a spiritual dimension, the impersonal public dole does nothing
to overcome &quot;behavioral poverty&quot;--the breakdown in values
and behavior needed to promote self-sufficiency and build stable
families.
<P>
 Michigan Governor John M. Engler recognized this in 1991 when
he embarked on what has become one of the most ambitious efforts
to reform welfare in the states.  Michigan abruptly ended the
General Assistance program for able-bodied, childless adults in
October 1991 and adopted a &quot;social contract,&quot; whereby
welfare recipients are expected to seek work, go to school, or
perform community service in exchange for benefits.
<P>
 To encourage work, the state now allows welfare recipients to
keep more of their earnings without having that count as income
against their welfare checks.  Before this change, the tax-free
value of AFDC, food stamps, and Medicaid for a family of three
in Michigan (about $1,000 per month) was roughly equal to the
income one could earn at a minimum wage or entry-level job.  This
hardly promoted work over welfare.
<P>
 The Engler reforms have produced tangible results.  Nearly 25
percent of Michigan's AFDC recipients are now working.  This is
three times the national average and up from 16 percent just two
years ago.  Average earnings from work and hours spent in volunteer
activity are up as well.  Fewer families are receiving assistance
than at any time since 1989.
<P>
 While those results are welcome, it's too early to break out
the champagne.  Governor Engler himself expressed a healthy skepticism
about both federal and state welfare reforms when he told ABC's
David Brinkley in November 1994, &quot;Replacing liberal micromanagement
with conservative micromanagement would only be a slight improvement;
it's time for wholesale reform.&quot;  By this, he means further
reducing the role of government and making welfare a largely private
initiative.  In the words of columnist John Fund of the <I>Wall
Street Journal</I>, &quot;Ask yourself: If you had a financial
windfall and wanted to help the poor, would you even <I>think</I>
about giving time or a check to the government?&quot;
<P>
 In Michigan, a growing number of private initiatives to help
the poor are already underway, some of which sprouted in direct
response to the state's abolition of General Assistance.  For
instance, Hard Times Cafe in Harrison provides counseling, job
placement, and other services to the needy.  Clients earn &quot;Hard
Times Dollars&quot; that are redeemable for personal-needs items
such as soap and toothpaste.  These are donated by individuals
and local businesses.
<P>
 With hardly a murmur about separation of church and state, the
state of Michigan has contracted with the Salvation Army to operate
a statewide network of 120 homeless shelters.  For the amazingly
low cost of $10 per person per day, the Army provides a bed, two
meals, and personal interaction with the needy aimed at reducing
behavioral poverty.
<P>
 The privatization of welfare could be pursued in a number of
ways.  A cold turkey approach would simply abolish welfare and
rely on families, churches, and charities to help the needy. 
The response might pleasantly surprise some who think that only
government can perform this task.  A more gradual transition to
a privatized scenario would provide more public recognition of
charities and greater incentives for charitable giving.  State
and local governments might also contract out more welfare services,
giving those in need a choice between increasingly proscriptive
and punitive government programs and private charity, which is
more likely to offer personalized help.
<P>
 Our welfare system has produced such disastrous consequences
that it's hard to imagine how a radical overhaul could make things
worse.  If we revitalize the American ideals of charity and self-help,
we might end up spending less for success than the government
now spends for failure.
<P>
<B><A NAME="mass">Massachusetts: Why State-Level Reform Won't Work</A></B>
<P>
<B>by David G. Tuerck</B>
<P>
 Welfare reform is progressing in many states.  Even if President
Clinton vetoes future federal welfare reform bills, a number of
states will continue to undertake reforms of their own.  Massachusetts,
justifiably infamous for its bloated welfare state, adopted sweeping
reforms last year under Governor William Weld:
<P>
<ul>
 <li>Ablebodied welfare recipients whose youngest children have
entered school must work at least 20 hours per week in a job or
community service program.
<P>
 <LI>Parents under age 18 must live with a responsible adult or
in a supervised group home.  They must stay in school or in a
GED program.
<P>
 <LI>A family cap denies additional benefits to recipients for children
born after August 1996.
<P>
 <LI>Ablebodied recipients' benefits are cut by 2.75 percent.
<P>
 </ul>Just to make a point, Massachusetts renamed its welfare bureaucracy:
the Department of Public Welfare became the Department of Transitional
Assistance.

<P>
 Overdue as these reforms are, they do not go to the heart of
the problem.  The reason lies in the method by which we fund welfare.
 Under the existing system, taxpayers send their money to Washington,
where most flows into a welfare bureaucracy and only a fraction
eventually reaches the pockets of the poor.  As long as welfare
is taxpayer-funded but government-controlled, it will remain an
expensive entitlement offered by a faceless bureaucracy.  The
seeds of poverty will be left to sprout anew.
<P>
 The best reform approach is to make welfare taxpayer-funded and
taxpayer-controlled.  A Beacon Hill Institute Policy Study, <I>Giving
Credit Where Credit Is Due: A New Approach to Welfare Funding</I>,
proposes that individual taxpayers, both itemizers and non-itemizers,
receive a 100 percent federal tax credit for contributions to
eligible charities for up to 25 percent of their federal tax liability.
 This would shift control of $115 billion in federal welfare spending
from government to individuals.  Eligible charities would be 501(c)(3)
organizations that offer services now provided by government under
meanstested programs, such as AFDC, Food Stamps, and housing assistance.
 These organizations would vie for taxpayer support by offering
superior services to the needy.
<P>
 Why so radical a proposal?  A few facts show why the welfare
system is broken.  Although the poverty rate declined from 1959
to 1994, there are still more than 38 million Americans (14.5
percent of the total population) living in poverty.  Poverty affects
women and children more than others.  The poverty rate was 54
percent for single female headsofhousehold in 1994.  The rate
for children rose from 14.9 percent in 1970 to 21.8 percent in
1994.
<P>
 These statistics stand out against the backdrop of a vastly expanded
welfare system.  Combined federal and state spending on direct
public aid increased tenfold from $15 billion in 1970 to $142
billion in 1990.  Furthermore, government welfare spending is
highly inefficient.  Only 41 percent of all povertylevel families
receive any government benefits at all.  And almost half of those
receiving benefits are not poor.  More than two-thirds of all
federal welfare spending ultimately ends up in the pockets of
people who are not poor.
<P>
 Welfare is commonly viewed as something the government provides.
 But this view is highly myopic.  Individuals currently give about
$17 billion to private charities that provide services similar
to those provided by government.  Total spending for direct-service
programs is about $132 billion, equal to the $115 billion spent
by the federal government plus $17 billion spent by private charities.
 Contrary to those who believe that charity cannot compensate
for a loss of government welfare payments, a tax credit can be
expected to increase the total amount of welfare for at least
four reasons:
<P>
<ul>
 <LI><I>Increased giving</I>.  The provision of a tax incentive
for charitable contributions amounts to a reduction in the price
of private giving.  This price is equal to the cost, after taxes,
of giving an additional dollar.  Under present law, the price
of giving for a federal taxpayer in the 28 percent tax bracket
is 72 cents.  A 100 percent tax credit would reduce this price
to zero (for donations up to a 25 percent limit).  Provision of
a full tax credit would cause private giving to expand by more
than tax revenues contract, thus causing the total amount of welfare
to expand.
<P>
 <LI><I>Increased voluntarism</I>.  A recent Gallup poll finds that
29 percent, or 70 million, of all Americans volunteer in their
communities.  Those who volunteer also give more to charities.
 The creation of a tax credit would add at least 2 million people
to the pool of volunteers.
<P>
 <LI><I>Increased efficiency and savings</I>.  Most research has
found that the private sector is more cost-efficient than government
in delivering services.  Moreover, nonprofit organizations rely
more on unpaid volunteers than either government or businesses.
<P>
 <LI><I>Reduced crowd-out</I>.  Government spending has been shown
to crowd out private giving.  A one-dollar increase in government
spending decreases private giving by an estimated 10 cents.  The
proposed 100 percent tax credit would eliminate this problem.
</ul>
<P>
 Devolving welfare to the states is one path to reform.  But it
will not succeed if states merely substitute their bureaucracies
for federal bureaucracies.  Optimum welfare reform would shift
responsibility for welfare to private charities.  And tax credits
are the most effective public-policy instrument for achieving
this change.
<P>
<B><A NAME="ind">Indiana: Reorienting Welfare</A></B>
<P>
<B>by Andrew Bush</B>
<P>
 Whether or not the federal government introduces welfare block
grants to the states, Indiana should use the considerable flexibility
it already has to transform the way it helps its neediest families.
 The focus of Indiana's welfare policy should be to help families
become self-sufficient.  Government can best achieve this goal
by recognizing its own limitations and by drawing on the strengths
of charities, community-based organizations, and other private
service providers.
<P>
 The Indianapolis Independence Initiative, or I-3, probably offers
the best model for reforming Indiana's welfare system.  As a graduated
work-based plan currently proposed as an alternative to AFDC in
Marion County, I-3 would dramatically change the orientation of
welfare in two ways:
<P>
<ul>
 <LI>Consistent employment by at least one parent is about the closest
thing there is to a ticket out of poverty.  I-3 would focus on
giving needy families that opportunity by helping able-bodied
parents find immediate work.  Unsubsidized, private-sector employment
would be the primary goal, but those not yet able to obtain such
employment could build their skills and work histories through
partially subsidized jobs or fully subsidized community-service
jobs.  Those with temporary disabilities could &quot;earn&quot;
cash support by performing tasks that would prepare them to support
their families.  I-3's focus on employment and earnings would
help families move quickly into the mainstream working world and
become acclimated to the lifestyle it demands.
<P>
 Rather than ending assistance when parents find jobs, I-3 would
treat initial employment as a first step.  Money used for welfare
benefits would be channeled into services and subsidies to help
low-income working parents remain employed and increase their
capacity to be self-supporting.  Child care, health care, employment
services, and counseling would be available to help families become
and remain employed.
<P>
 <LI>I-3 would open public aid to a wide range of non-government
service providers that would help families pursue self-sufficiency.
 Networks of provider organizations would operate under performance-based
contracts.  By opening up the public-assistance provider system
and judging organizations by performance standards, public assistance
would become more useful, creative, and efficient.
</ul>
<P>
 Private charities and other community-based organizations have
an important role to play in systems such as I-3.  The danger
is that they might seek to recreate the current welfare system.
 It is essential that charities summon all their creativity and
expertise to make work-based public assistance a reality.
<P>
<B><A NAME="wis">Wisconsin: Work Requirements for All Welfare Recipients</A></B>
<P>
<B>by Michael E. Hartmann</B>
<P>
 Wisconsin has imposed stringent work requirements on welfare
recipients and has successfully moved many able-bodied recipients
into productive work.  Only hard-core recipients remain on welfare
in Wisconsin.  A bill that has just passed both houses of the
state legislature by wide margins, &quot;W-2--Wisconsin Works,&quot;
would require all recipients to work.  Spearheaded by Governor
Tommy G. Thompson, it is likely to be signed into law this April.
<P>
 A January 1995 study by welfare expert Lawrence W. Mead found
that between 1989 and 1993, the national AFDC caseload grew by
29 percent, from 10.2 million to 14.1 million.  State caseloads
increased by an average of 35 percent.  But according to the Wisconsin
Department of Health and Social Services, Wisconsin's welfare
caseload fell by 24.5 percent from January 1987 to July 1995--from
98,300 to 70,300 cases.  According to Mead, this was partly because
Wisconsin implemented the Job Opportunities and Basic Skills (JOBS)
program in 1988.  Mandated by Title II of the federal Family Support
Act, JOBS required caseworkers to closely monitor and motivate
welfare recipients in their search for employment.
<P>
 In July 1993, Wisconsin implemented an even tougher employment
requirement for some AFDC recipients, called &quot;Work, Not Welfare&quot;
(WNW).  WNW limits AFDC payments to two years and offers major
job-training services.  To determine the number of hours a recipient
must work or participate in training, WNW combines food stamps
and AFDC into one lump-sum payment that is then divided by the
federal minimum wage ($4.25).  WNW can be credited with reducing
AFDC rolls in Fond du Lac County from 627 in December 1994 to
385 in July 1995 (a 38.6 percent decline), and in Pierce County
from 191 in December 1994 to 117 in July 1995 (a 38.7 percent
decline).
<P>
 If signed by Governor Thompson as expected, the latest proposal--W-2--Wisconsin
Works--will create a &quot;self-sufficiency ladder&quot; for welfare
recipients based on four graduated work options:
<P>
<ul> 
<LI><i>W-2 Transitions</I>.  Recipients unable to perform self-sustaining
work will engage in work activities (e.g., sheltered workshops),
vocational rehabilitation, and counseling.  Twenty-eight hours
of work activity plus 12 hours of job training at $518 per month
will be imposed.  Food stamps will be available.  A time limit
of 24 months may be extended on a case-by-case basis.
<P>
<LI><I>Community-service jobs</I>.  Recipients will learn work
habits and job skills necessary for employment in the private
sector.  Thirty hours of work per week plus ten hours of training
at $555 per month will be imposed.  Like W-2 Transitions, food
stamps will be available and participation will be limited to
24 months.
<P>
<LI> <I>Trial jobs (subsidized employment)</I>.  Recipients' transition
to unsubsidized private employment will initially be subsidized--for
example, when a recipient is willing to work but has little or
no work history.  Forty hours of work per week at market wages
will be imposed, and employers will receive up to $300 per month
in subsidies.  Food stamps and the Earned Income Tax Credit (EITC)
will be available.  Time in the program will be limited to 24
months.
<P>
 <LI><I>Unsubsidized employment</I>.  Recipients will be guided
to the best available immediate job in the private sector.  Forty
hours of work per week at market wages will be imposed, and food
stamps and the EITC will be available.
</ul><P>
 The bill that has just passed the state legislature says that
&quot;the W-2 agency will operate the four major components .
. . in an integrated fashion so that participants are always entering
the highest (i.e., least subsidized) workforce stage possible,
and are moving up to the next level at the earliest opportunity.&quot;
 Those eligible for participation will be &quot;families consisting
of custodial parents and their children age 18 or younger, with
incomes below 115 percent of poverty and with low assets.&quot;
 Health-care and child-care benefits (to which recipients must
make co-payments) are included.  However, to meet predictable
legal challenges to the program by those denied benefits, the
bill states that &quot;an individual is not entitled to benefits
or services under [W-2].&quot;
<P>
 The state legislature modified the governor's original proposal
by:
<P>
<ul>
<LI>Strengthening health-care provisions for pregnant mothers and
new mothers;
<P>
 <LI>Lowering participants' co-payments for child care;
<P>
 <LI>Allowing those in vocational or four-year college programs
to complete their schooling without losing benefits;
</ul>
<P>
 Democratic Assembly Minority Leader Walter J. Kunicki remarked
before passage that &quot;People are afraid not to vote for [W-2].
 No one wants to be on record voting against welfare reform.&quot;
 W-2 is expected to affect more than 53,000 women and their children
and cost $2.1 billion in its first two years--$110 more than under
current welfare spending.
<P>
  Hopefully, Congress will soon pass block grant welfare legislation.
 Otherwise, Wisconsin will have to seek waivers from the Department
of Health and Human Services to implement W-2.  Nonetheless, state
welfare officials see W-2's self-sufficiency ladder as a realistic
way to encourage all welfare recipients, even those heretofore
considered unemployable, to become productive members of society.
<P>
<B><A NAME="colo">Colorado: An Agenda for the State Legislature</A></B>
<P>
<B>by Tom Tancredo and Dwight Filley</B>
<P>
 What if one thing caused most of Colorado's social ills?  And
what if government policies were encouraging that one thing?
<P>
 If these two statements are true, then we can go a long way toward
curing those ills by simply reversing the policies that encourage
that single development.  There is a growing body of evidence
linking the following social pathologies to a common factor: juvenile
delinquency, drug abuse, gang membership, dropping out of school,
homelessness, teenage pregnancy, illiteracy, high infant mortality,
poor prenatal care, poverty, and welfare dependency.  That factor
is the absence of a married father in the household.  Obviously,
the lack of a father is not the only cause, but there is a strong
correlation between these problems and a childhood spent in a
fatherless home.
<P>
 One might think that in an advanced Western democracy, public
policy would be directed toward reducing the number of fatherless
homes and toward encouraging marriage.  But current federal policy
does exactly the opposite.  It penalizes those who are married
and rewards those who are not.
<P>
 The penalties?  A couple considering marriage must get permission
from the government by obtaining a license.  If the government
approves, the couple must pay a fee--a fine if you will.  Once
married, the couple will probably pay a much larger fine--the
so-called marriage penalty of the federal income tax.  They must
pay the fine every year they remain married.  Newspapers have
carried stories about couples who divorce and then live together
to reduce their income taxes.
<P>
 And the rewards for being unmarried?  Government benefits: housing
vouchers, food stamps, day care, and a cash reward--AFDC--that
is paid every month for a child born out of wedlock.  In most
states, this reward is increased with each additional child.
<P>
 What we have here, as they say, is a failure to communicate.
 If the single strongest predictor of the above-mentioned problems
is the absence of a father, why does government policy seem geared
toward driving fathers away?
<P>
 Although Colorado lives under an oppressive burden of federal
laws, we still have considerable latitude to end the perverse
incentives that wreck families and contribute to our social ills.
 AFDC, for example, is a matching fund program.  If the Colorado
legislature refused to fund its share, AFDC would end in the state.
 Similarly, Colorado could revise its income tax code to offset
the federal marriage penalty.
<P>
 The state legislature might also take the following considerations
into account in drafting welfare reform legislation:
<P>
<ul>
 <LI>Recognize that shielding people from the natural consequences
of their destructive actions will result in more destructive actions.
<P>
<LI> Freeze welfare spending at current levels.  This is the only
way to reduce welfare in the long run.
<P>
 <LI>Do not cut funding for current welfare programs that provide
for the disabled and the elderly.
<P>
 <LI>Do not provide government assistance to people who can work.
 If such people are forced to be accountable to their families,
churches, communities, and private charities, they are more likely
to enter the job market and end their destructive behavior than
if they receive aid from an impersonal bureaucracy.  When Michigan
terminated General Assistance for employable, childless adults,
welfare rolls fell by 82,000, and welfare payments by 17 percent.
<P>
 <LI>Enact a meaningful workfare program.  Do not allow a two-year
waiting period before applying workfare requirements.  If workfare
is to succeed in discouraging able-bodied people from going on
welfare, its effect will be strongest at the time of welfare enrollment,
not two years later.
<P>
 <LI>Workfare costs taxpayers more when unmarried mothers have children
under the age of five, because day-care must be provided.  Accordingly,
apply workfare first to able-bodied recipients other than mothers
with young children.  However, mothers who choose to have additional
children while already on welfare should not be exempt from workfare
requirements.
<P>
 <LI>Do not provide welfare to women under 18 unless they live with
a parent or legal guardian.  Too often, the prospect of money
for one's own apartment is an incentive to become pregnant.  Exceptions
should be made if teenagers have left home because of abuse, and
if teenagers lived independently for at least a year before applying
for welfare.
<P>
<LI> Do not increase payments to women who bear more children while
they are welfare recipients.  Working parents get no pay raise
when they have more children.  This policy is already law in New
Jersey, where the number of births to welfare recipients has fallen
by 16 percent.
<P>
<LI> Make AFDC funding contingent upon the mother identifying the
father, if the child was born after 1994.  DNA testing can verify
or refute disputes about paternity.  Require all fathers of AFDC
children born in 1995 or thereafter to pay child support.  If
the father claims that he cannot find employment, put him to work
in community service.  As word spreads that fathering an illegitimate
child will result in a two-decade-long financial obligation, fewer
men may be tempted to &quot;prove their masculinity.&quot;
<P>
 <LI>Consider abolishing AFDC altogether.  Redistribute AFDC funds
to group homes for unwed mothers, adoption programs and, possibly,
orphanages.  A cut-off for AFDC benefits could be phased in to
apply first to women under age 18 (or 21), then extended to women
25 and under (who bear two-thirds of all illegitimate children),
and then to the entire population.  Group homes and orphanages
should be carefully evaluated.
<P>
 <LI>Encourage sex education programs that promote abstinence. 
Many of these have cut pregnancy rates by 40 percent.  By contrast,
programs that provide contraceptive information have virtually
no success in reducing pregnancy.

<P>
<LI> Encourage adoption as the best choice for women who bear children
and lack the resources to raise them properly.
</ul>
<P>
 (Greg Bledsoe, Dwight Filley, Tim Garrett, Andrew Kelley, Dave
Kopel, and Ben Kwitek contributed to this article.)
<P>
<B><A NAME="washi">Washington State: Two Views</A></B>
<P>
<B>I. Needed: A Strong Dose of Common Sense</B>
<P>
<B>by John Carlson</B>
<P>
 &quot;We absolutely will not tolerate the sort of back-door discrimination
against families and children that many today call 'welfare reform.'&quot;
 I can understand Washington Governor Mike Lowry making that statement
in 1966.  But in 1996?  Such unabashed '60s-speak explains much
about the governor's political unpopularity.  He has not learned
from experience.  Experience should tell him that efforts to reform
welfare don't discriminate against the family--the status quo
does.  A young mother can receive a welfare check only if she
doesn't marry the father, doesn't live at home, doesn't find a
job, and doesn't save any money.  You can't get much more anti-family
than that.
<P>
 Statistics bear this out.  Between 1962 and 1992, welfare spending
in the U.S. went up by nearly 1,000 percent in inflation-adjusted
dollars.  At the same time, as former Education Secretary William
Bennett recently wrote in <I>Commentary</I> magazine, poverty
dropped by less than five percent, and illegitimacy soared by
400 percent.  As single-parent households have proliferated, so
have crime rates, drug abuse, drop-out rates in inner-city schools
and teenage pregnancy, keeping the cycle of decay in perpetual
motion.
<P>
 A couple of years ago, after a gang-related shoot-out in one
of Tacoma's rough neighborhoods, a TV station sent in a camera
crew to get people's reactions.  As expected, community leaders
on the scene called for more jobs, fewer guns, and better social
programs.  But one local women knew better.  She looked at the
reporter and simply told the stark truth: &quot;You gotta start
asking, where are the fathers?  What happened to all the men?&quot;
<P>
 That is the question our welfare system cannot answer.  Young
men who father children out of wedlock don't have to take responsibility
for their actions.  The welfare system does it for them.  And
the mother isn't required to identify the father of the child.
 Again, you can't get much more anti-family than that.
<P>
 So what's the answer?  Before getting specific, let's be clear
about standards.  Welfare is supposed to be a temporary, stop-gap
measure to help people who have fallen on hard times.  In that
sense, we should apply the same kind of common sense to welfare
reform that we would use if someone in our own family experienced
trouble.
<P>
 Suppose your divorced sister lost her job.  She has two kids.
 Naturally, you would want to help.  First, you'd give or loan
her some money to pay some bills due at the end of the month.
 Then you'd try to help her find a job.  You'd back up her efforts
to get child support from her ex-husband.  You might buy her some
groceries.
<P>
 But for how long?  Suppose she stopped looking for work.  Suppose
you found out she was using your temporary financial help to buy
drugs.  Or that she was just hanging out with friends at the local
tavern.  Suppose she let her husband off the hook for child support.
 Would you keep subsidizing her behavior?  Of course not.  Which
raises the question, If you wouldn't subsidize the irresponsible
or illegal behavior of your own sister, why are we doing it through
our welfare system for complete strangers?
<P>
 Suppose your sister wasn't irresponsible--she just wasn't motivated.
 Let's say she couldn't find a job that paid as much as she was
earning before.  Wouldn't you expect her to accept a temporary
job that paid less and wait for a better-paying job to come along?
 Would you keep sending her money if she refused to take a lower-paying
job?  What if she couldn't find any jobs in the small town where
she lived?  Wouldn't you tell her after awhile that it was time
to move on to a place where she could find employment?
<P>
 This is the kind of genuine safety net that family members erect
for each other hundreds of thousands of times a year.  It is a
net that would unravel if not tightly woven with reasonable and
sensible expectations about how best to help others.  Why not
apply that same common sense to our welfare system?
<P>
 Fortunately, state Representative Suzette Cooke (R-Kent) has
crafted a welfare reform bill that begins to do exactly that.
 It would limit welfare benefits and include an additional period
of reduced benefits for welfare recipients who are working.  Recipients
who don't look for work would have their benefits reduced.  They
could save money without being penalized, but cash benefits would
not be increased for recipients who have more children.
<P>
 Governor Lowry might find this unfair, but I know him well enough
to say that if he were spending his own money to help someone
in his family, he'd find these conditions perfectly reasonable.
 Extending these standards of common sense to government programs
is long overdue.
<P>
<B><A NAME="washii">II. Dismantling the Welfare Culture</A></B>
<P>
<B>by Lynn Harsh and Bob Williams</B>
<P>
 There she was: a teenage mother pleading her case on TV, warning
state lawmakers of the hardships she would face if her welfare
payments were reduced.  The nicely-dressed, high school dropout
lived with her middle-class parents, but they were financially
stretched, she explained.  The baby's father?  He was not helping
out, nor did she expect him to.  She said that she needed more
time on welfare to get a college education.
<P>
 It was a picture of a welfare system gone awry--a system undergirding
promiscuity and making fatherhood irrelevant; rewarding personal
irresponsibility with a free trip to college; and allowing able
grandparents to shift the responsibility of caring for their grandchild
to the government.  Most Americans have heard similar stories
and realize that the &quot;welfare culture&quot; created by our
current system must be changed.
<P>
 In reviewing new welfare responsibilities that might soon become
the responsibility of states, legislators need to carefully examine
each current program and ask:
<P>
<ul>
 <LI>Is the program a proper function of government?
<P>
 <LI>What is the program's mission, and is that mission worth pursuing?
<P>
<LI>Given the option, would we have mandated the program?  If not,
can it be eliminated?
<P>
 <LI>If government at some level should operate the program, how
can it be done in the most efficient and cost-effective manner?
</ul><P>
 Block-granting welfare money to states should only be viewed
as a short-term approach since it does not substantially change
the relationship between givers (taxpayers) and receivers (welfare
recipients).  As soon as possible, givers must become individuals
and private charities, not different levels of government.  To
move in that direction, states should block grant funds directly
to counties and require them to contract out the delivery of welfare
services on a strict performance basis.  Counties should receive
incentives for involving private charities, and block grants at
all levels should be reduced over time.
<P>
 Washington state legislators began serious welfare reform negotiations
in 1995.  Talks broke down when the Senate refused to discuss
limiting the number of months recipients could collect benefits.
 Negotiations began again this year, but once again faltered over
the issues of time limits, family caps, and cash payments to recipients.
 The House proposal, which will likely be revived again next year,
moves in the right direction.  Among its major provisions:
<P>
<ul>
 <LI>A maximum of 36 months of assistance.  Benefits would be cut
over time.  However, there would be exemptions to the time limit
for those caring for an incapacitated person, a child under two,
and for victims of domestic or sexual assault.
<P>
 <LI> Recipients would sign contracts outlining their responsibilities
and would be required to participate in a job-training and job-search
program (with certain exemptions).
<P>
<LI> Unwed teen mothers would receive no cash payments and would
be restricted in their living arrangements and in the amount of
benefits they could receive.
<P>
<LI> Recipients in job programs would receive full child care and
transitional child care.
<P>
<LI> Unwed mothers would be required to identify the fathers of
their children.
</ul><P>
 We recommend that the state legislature also undertake the following
reforms:
<P>
<ul>
<LI> Stringently enforce child support.
<P>
<LI> Ease restrictions that make adoption difficult.
<P>
<LI> Ease regulations on private charities and offer greater tax
incentives for charitable contributions.
<P>
<LI> Change program incentives so that state welfare agencies redefine
success as the number of people removed from welfare rolls and
placed in long-term employment.
</ul>
<P>
 Interestingly, the mere talk of tough welfare reform seems to
be having an effect.  Fewer people are applying for welfare in
Washington state than last year despite no significant changes
in the law or the economy.  Experts have no explanation for this.
<P>
 We are, however, concerned about the curt dismissal of some programs
that are religious in nature.  Religion-based charities have a
far better track record of helping the needy than centralized
bureaucratic programs.  Mississippi Governor Kirk Fordice's program,
&quot;Faith and Families,&quot; should be replicated in Washington.
 It pairs welfare recipients with a church of their choice and
offers personal, practical, and spiritual guidance.
<P>
 Hundreds of charities, nonprofit organizations, and privatesector
job-training and placement programs already serve the needy. 
Many of them have a proven record of operating efficiently and
with a high degree of accountability.  In the long run, we advocate
abolishing government-run welfare entirely.  Far from being a
cruel or reckless approach, this change would help renew our families,
neighborhoods, churches, and communities--the institutions best
able to serve the needy.  Each of us must set an example and lead
the way.  No government program can compete with that kind of
first-person compassion.
<P><BR><P>
</BODY>

